{ It was essential to prevent the arrival of the black knight on d4 by   7.Be3  On the other hand, it is too late to try to unpin after castling:   7.h3  Bh5  of course, Black maintains the pin and does not exchange on f3  8.g4  A headlong rush that seriously weakens the kingside, but it is difficult to go back. Black threatens 8...Nd4  or maybe, in the longer term, queenside castling followed by a pawn attack involving ...g5-g4 to open lines and try to exploit the move h2-h3.  8...Bg6  and Black will take advantage of the weakening of the white kingside by castling queenside himself, and then by playing ...h7-h5 with a very strong attack.  One could of course also consider sacrificing a piece for two pawns:   8...Nxg4  9.hxg4  Bxg4  and Black will get strong pressure on the f3-knight after moves like ...Nd4 or ...Qf6. }
