1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6 3. Bc4
{ This was the first time that Guillaume played the Grand Prix Attack. He was therefore not yet aware of the move-order subtleties.   3.f4  is obviously the normal move. }
3... b5 4. Be2
{ The bishop went out a little early and must return home pronto.   4.Bb3  is not possible because of  c4 }
4... Bb7 5. d3
{ The light-squared bishop is now confined to its camp. Too bad, but this is not very serious. As mentioned in the introduction, this is not a piece that is essential for the attack. }
5... d6 6. f4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. O-O Nf6 9. Qe1
{ The queen heads towards the theatre of operations. } 9... O-O
{ One could criticize this move by arguing that Black castles cemetery side, but it is just as unthinkable to leave the king in the centre. Moreover, at this point Black had no idea of what was about to befall him. }
10. Qh4 Nbd7 11. f5 { The signal to attack, it will almost play itself. } 11...
b4 12. Nd1
{ If the knight had gone to d5 it would have immediately been eliminated by the b7-bishop. A note from Chessable:   12.Nd5  Bxd5 }
12... a5
{ Black has no counterplay on the queenside, and, by the looks of it, he is unaware of the impending danger on the other wing. }
13. Bh6 a4
{ Black heads straight into the wall, but it is very difficult to defend against the white attack that unfolds. }
14. Ng5
{ The Grand Prix Attack in all its splendour ! Note in particular the model arrangement of the bishop on h6, the knight on g5 and the queen on h4. Not to mention the f1-rook, ready to intervene as soon as the f-file opens. }
14... Ne5
{ Black precipitates his defeat by removing one of the protectors of the f6-knight. His position was already compromised in any case. To eliminate the two black knights that mutually defend themselves, White would have played Ne3-g4, and he would then have sacrificed the exchange as in the game. }
15. fxg6 hxg6
{ 15...fxg6 ?  16.Ne6  +-   15...Nxg6  was the only move, but after  16.Qh3  Bc8  17.g4  White retains a strong attack. }
16. Rxf6 { Naturally ! } 16... Bxf6 17. Bg7
{ The elegant tactical conclusion to remember when there is no longer an h7-pawn. We will meet it again.   17.Bxf8 ?  would have been a big mistake. After  Kxf8  the white attack would have ground to a halt. A wonderful and yet simple example of the Grand Prix Attack in action. }
