1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. f4 Nc6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4
{ This comes as no surprise from Nigel Short, who is one of the English GMs that popularized the Grand Prix Attack. He has played it very frequently, even at the highest level. }
5... Bg7 6. O-O e6 7. d3 Nge7 8. Qe1 Nd4
{ A logical continuation, which attacks the c2-pawn and forces the exchange of the f3-knight, which is an important piece for the white attack. }
9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Ne2 O-O
{ 10...d5  is premature because of  11.Bb5+ !  Bd7  12.Bxd7+  Qxd7  13.e5  Nc6  14.b4 !  The d4-pawn is very weak and will be attacked after Bb2. }
11. Bb3 { The bishop retreats in order to answer 11. Bb3 d5 with 12. e5. }
11... Nc6 12. Bd2 d5 13. e5
{ Black is now safe from the f4-f5 move, but problems of another nature have emerged: the dark squares around the king can become weak, as can the d4-pawn. }
13... f6 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Kh1
{ This is the start of a subtle plan. White wants to redeploy his knight to f3 to control the e5-square, while continuing to put pressure on the d4-pawn. }
15... a5 16. a4 Qd6 17. Ng1 Bd7 18. Nf3 Nb4 19. Qf2
{ Played both to attack the weakness on d4 and to pre-emptively defend the c2-pawn. }
19... Qc5 20. Bc3
{ A nice tactical point that attacks the d4-pawn a third time and which therefore forces the b4-knight to retreat. }
20... Nc6
{ Obviously, the d4-pawn was pinned because of the unprotected position of the black queen, and therefore it could not take the c3-bishop. }
21. Rae1 b6 22. Bd2 Nb4
{ Now that the queen is protected, the knight returns, but White has gained the move Rae1 in the process. Instead, Black should have been thinking of defence by playing 22... Rae8. }
23. Qg3 b5
{ Too optimistic. Now it was absolutely necessary to play 23... Rae8.   23...Nxc2 ?  however, was not possible because of  24.Rc1 }
24. f5
{ The thematic Grand Prix Attack move, although here it occurs at an unusual moment, and, above all, under different conditions. The main idea is to undermine the protection of the d5-pawn and thus bring the b3-bishop back to life. }
24... exf5 25. Ne5
{ The point of White's pawn sacrifice; the knight obtains a dominant central position, and cannot be exchanged. }
25... Be8
{ 25...Bxe5 ?  26.Qxe5  Rae8  27.Bxb4  axb4  28.Bxd5+  The light-squared bishop returns to the game in a decisive manner. }
26. axb5
{ A small finesse before capturing on f5. White avoids the capture on a4, and threatens 27. c3, which wins the knight. }
26... Qxb5 27. Rxf5 Kh8 28. Rxf6
{ This time it is not a knight that the rook eliminates, but the bishop that defends the dark squares. }
28... Rxf6 29. Ng4 Rf5 { 29...Rf8  30.Qe5+  Kg8  31.Nh6# } 30. Nh6 Rh5
{ If the rook leaves the 5th rank, it's mate after 31. Qe5+. } 31. Qf4
{ Black resigned. He can no longer defend the dark squares around his king. f8, f6 and d4 are all in the white queen's sights. }
