1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6
{ Anand is not an unbridled fan of the Grand Prix Attack like Nigel Short, but the Indian World Champion's move order conceals a subtlety on which it is interesting to pause for a moment. Boris Gelfand is a leading expert on the Najdorf Variation of the Sicilian, which he plays almost exclusively when he opens with 1... c5. In the Najdorf main lines, Black rarely develops his knight to c6, but rather to d7. As we have already mentioned and which will be seen in more detail in the next game , the black move 2... d6 is not the most precise against the Grand Prix Attack. Better is 2... Nc6, in order to leave the d-pawn in its starting blocks and to eventually play ... d7-d5 in one move, thus saving a tempo compared to Game 33. However, if Gelfand had replied 2... Nc6, Anand probably planned to continue with 3. Nf3 and to branch off into another Open Sicilian after 4. d4 . Then the Israeli would not have been able to play his favourite Najdorf any more since his knight was already on c6. As a result, Gelfand preferred to face a Grand Prix Attack with the move ...d7-d6, rather than an Open Sicilian other than the Najdorf. A risky choice. }
3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 Nc6 6. d3 e6 7. O-O Nge7 8. Qe1 h6
{ After his defeat against Short, Gelfand tries an alternative to 8... Nd4. The idea of the text move is to defer kingside castling in order to see White's intentions. }
9. Bb3
{ A precautionary retreat to avoid the bishop being attacked after an eventual ...d7-d5, as in the previous game. }
9... a6
{ A game of cat and mouse. Black plays another waiting move, which could allow him to be active on the queenside with ...b7-b5 later in the game.  Due to the move ... h7-h6, castling kingside would be even more risky than in the usual continuations seen previously:   9...O-O ?  10.f5 !  and Qh4 attacks the h6-pawn straight away. }
10. e5
{ A pawn sacrifice designed to exploit the weakened dark squares on the kingside. }
10... Nf5
{ 10...dxe5  11.fxe5  Nxe5  12.Nxe5  Qd4+  13.Kh1  Qxe5  14.Ne4  and the threat 15. Bf4 gives White too much play for the pawn. An example:  O-O ?!   14...Qc7  15.Bf4  e5  16.Bxf7+ !  +-  15.Bxh6 !  Bxh6  16.Nf6+  +- }
11. Kh1 { A prophylactic move to avoid any checks on the a7-g1 diagonal. }
11... Nfd4 12. Ne4
{ To increase the pressure on the dark squares f6, d6, and c5. } 12... Nxf3 13.
Rxf3 { 13.Nxd6+ ?  Qxd6  -+ } 13... dxe5 14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. Rf1 g5
{ Castling was not possible owing to the weakness caused by the move 8... h6:   15...O-O ?  16.Bxh6 !  Bxh6  17.Nf6+  Kg7  18.Qxe5  Qd4  19.Qg3 !  Qxb2  20.Rae1  followed by Re4 and Rh4 with a very strong attack. }
16. Qg3 O-O
{ After   16...b6  17.Bf4 !  Qc7  18.Rae1  White is clearly better. } 17. Bxg5
{ A sacrifice that was in the air and that you could see coming. 17. Nxc5 restored the material balance and gave an approximately equal position. }
17... hxg5 18. Nxg5 Ng6 19. Rae1
{ Mobilizing the final piece.   19.Qg4 ?  would be hasty due to  Qd4  20.Qh5  Qh4  -+ }
19... Qe7
{ In his comments, Anand devoted lengthy analysis to the moves 19... Bf6 and 19... Bxb2. Obviously there is no question of reproducing it here, all the more so since this is not essential for the assessment of the opening. }
20. Rf5 { In order to protect the knight before playing Qh3. } 20... Bf6
{ 20...Bh6  gives, according to Anand, a decisive white attack after  21.h4 ! }
21. Nxe6 fxe6
{ The decisive mistake. 21... Re8 ! left black with good chances to escape. }
22. Rxe6
{ The most accurate.   22.Bxe6+ ?  Bxe6  23.Rxe6  Qg7   22.Qxg6+ ?  Qg7  gives White nothing. }
22... Kg7
{ 22...Bxe6  23.Qxg6+  Qg7   23...Bg7  24.Bxe6+  24.Bxe6+  Kh8  25.Rh5+  and it's mate ! }
23. Rxe7+ Bxe7 24. Rxf8 Bxf8 25. h4 *

