wards:  1. Black plays ...d6-d5, and we exactly return to the previous structure.  2. Black accepts an exchange of the pawns e5 and d6. In this case, the c5-pawn is again very weak.  @@HeaderStart@@Structure nÂ°3@@HeaderEnd@@    Black has not played ...e7-e6, and he leaves his pawn on d6 to provide the best protection of the c5-pawn. However, with such a structure the g8-knight cannot develop to e7 and will have to settle for the f6-square. White will then return to his first love: the traditional attack on the kingside, based on f4-f5 and âe1-h4. The absence of light-squared bishops, as we know, is not critical. }
