{ @@HeaderStart@@Comanchero! The Kingâs Indian Attack against the French@@HeaderEnd@@  1.e4 e6  The French Defence, one of the oldest and most respectable answers to 1.e4. It was thus baptised after a correspondence match between London and Paris which took place from 1834 to 1836, and in which the French had answered 1...e6 to 1.e4. The French Defence has subsequently withstood the test of time. In terms of popularity it is today located 3rd of the defences the most played against 1.e4, following 1...e5 and the Sicilian. The former World Champion Mikhail Botvinnik and the later challenger Viktor Kortchnoi both notably made it their main weapon in their respective fight for the title.  Compared to 1...e5, the first Black move in the French   1...e6  seems modest and even passive  (as it restricts the c8-bishop)  , but it contains profound strategic ideas. First and foremost, Black seeks to establish a solid wall on the a2-g8 diagonal, thereby putting paid to all those ultra-fast attacks on the f7-pawn so frequent in the open games. In other words, no more Scholarâs Mate or even our Fegatello Attack from the 2nd chapter.  On the almost automatic response 2.d4 Black will then counter-attack against the e4-pawn by playing ...d7-d5, thereby seeking to provoke the white advance to e5. A closed position will then ensue â which is what Black is usually looking for in the French Defence â where the second playerâs chances are in no way inferior. Thanks to the moves ...c7-c5 and ...f7-f6 that he keeps up his sleeve, Black will be able to obtain satisfactory counterplay against the white centre.  Of course, as with the Sicilian, it is not our intention to embark on a study of the main variations of the French Defence. This is undoubtedly fascinating, but letâs leave it to experienced players  (or to those who have the time)  and let us be content, at least at first, to adopt a system that is easy to learn, and above all easy to understand.   The Kingâs Indian Attack that I am proposing against the French Defence fits perfectly into this framework. As early as the 2nd move, by playing 2.d3 rather than the mechanical 2.d4, White will avoid the main lines and lead Black into positions which will probably be less familiar to him.    The Kingâs Indian Attack is more a universal method of development than a specific variation. It is characterized by the moves âf3, g2-g3, âg2, d2-d3, âbd2, e2-e4 and 0-0, which can be played in  (almost)  any order. Well, let us say with several different move orders, and not just by starting with 1.e4.   Regardless of the path used, here is the basic position  (the tabiya, to use a chess term!)  to which White should arrive after eight moves.    Experienced players and those with a good memory will immediately recognize the development scheme of the Kingâs Indian Defence   an opening after  1.d4  . In fact, the Kingâs Indian Attack is actually only a Kingâs Indian Defence with colours reversed, and with an extra tempo  (which is not so important)  .  The Kingâs Indian Attack has several advantages:  â¢ It can virtually be played against every black opening, even without starting with 1.e4   for example with  1.âf3  or even  1.g3  . However, of course, we will only study it against the French   and by starting with  1.e4!  . Moreover, theory considers that it is against the French that the Kingâs Indian Attack is the most effective, because of the fact that the c8-bishop has already been closed in by the move ...e7-e6.  â¢ It is easy to play, as there are no major theoretical lines to recite by heart. You just have to know which squares to put the pieces on, and recognize the manoeuvres and thematic combinations that we will study in this chapter. I emphasize once again the fact that the understanding of an opening is much more important than the memorization of lengthy variations. This was true in the previous chapter with the Grand Prix Attack against the Sicilian. It will be again in the next chapter with the Yugoslav Attack against the kingâs fianchetto, and it is just as important â possibly even more so â with the Kingâs Indian Attack.  â¢ It often gives rise to rich and exciting attacking positions, as we will see.  â¢ It was played by several World Champions, starting with Fischer, who made it one of his main weapons against  the French and the Sicilian, but also by Botvinnik and Vassily Smyslov. Today, grandmasters of the highest order such as Alexander Morozevich or Victor Bologan use it regularly. This is the best proof of the soundness of this opening. Our study cannot be exhaustive, and so in this chapter we will confine ourselves to the three principal modes of development that Black can adopt in the French Defence against the Kingâs Indian Attack.  I. The classic variation, in which Black castles kingside after having developed the knight to f6 and the  bishop to e7    II. Black develops his bishop to g7, his knight to e7, and castles kingside    III. Black castles queenside    Here we go, and we start quite naturally with the âClassicâ Variation, which, as its name suggests, is the most frequently played line. }
