8. O-O-O Qa5 9. Kb1
{ A move which is always useful, to protect the a2-pawn, and to leave the c1-square for a knight that can help protect the king. Avoid the move 9. a3 as much as possible, as that would allow Black to open lines by playing ...b5-b4. As a general rule, try to refrain from playing pawn moves on the side where you are being attacked. This is not the first time that we encounter this maxim, which will never be repeated often enough. }
9... b4 10. Nce2 Nbd7 11. g4
{ The traditional continuation of the attack, to prepare h4-h5.  White can also consider playing   11.h5 !?  without preparation. If Black takes, then after  11...Nxh5  12.g4  Nhf6  the h-file is opened and the white attack has gained speed. It is generally thought that an open file against the king is worth a pawn especially in the presence of opposite castling . Another maxim to remember ! }
11... Rb8 12. h5 Nb6
{ Unlike White, Black does not have the opportunity to open lines towards the opposing king. The white attack is therefore the most dangerous. }
13. Nc1
{ The right square for the knight. It reinforces the protection of the a2-pawn and the b3-square, and de-congests the e2-square and the f1-a6 diagonal. White obviously could not tolerate the move 13... Nc4 which was threatened. }
13... Ba6 14. Nb3 Qa4 15. Bh6
{ White continues his attack unhindered. It is probably already decisive. }
15... Bxf1 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. hxg6 { Regardless of the f1-bishop ! } 17... fxg6
{ 17...hxg6 ?  18.Qh6+  Kg8  19.Qh8#   17...Bc4  18.Qh6+  Kg8  19.g7 !  Rfd8  20.g5  Â± }
18. Qh6+ Kg8 19. g5
{ White does not waste time recapturing the f1-bishop. The f6-knight must be eliminated to mate on h7. }
19... Nh5
{ Black believes that he will obtain some respite by closing the h-file, but it is illusory, as we shall see.  He had to try   19...Qb5  20.gxf6  Rf7  even though this was probably only delaying the inevitable. }
20. Rxh5 { A very common finish in this kind of attack. } 20... gxh5 21. g6
hxg6 22. Qxg6+ Kh8 23. Nh3
{ As much to threaten to play 24. Ng5 as to free the 1st rank for the rook. Black has no defence. }
23... Bxh3
{ The bishop finally emerges while eliminating the dangerous knight. } 24.
Qxh5+ Kg7 25. Rg1+ Kf6 26. Qg6#
{ The black bishop has not even been taken. We meet the future GM now still aged 14 again in the next game, also in the role of Dragon Slayer. }
